  "prompt": "Why does Ramsay Bolton treat Sansa Stark that way on their wedding night?",
  "response": "Ramsay Bolton's brutal treatment of Sansa Stark on their wedding night in *Game of Thrones* stems from a combination of his personal sadism, political strategy, and psychological manipulation:\n\n1. **Sadistic Nature**: Ramsay derives pleasure from inflicting pain and humiliation. His actions are driven by a deeply ingrained cruelty, reflecting his enjoyment of dominance and control over others.\n\n2. **Political Domination**: The marriage to Sansa is a Bolton ploy to legitimize their rule over the North by merging their name with the Stark legacy. By violating Sansa, Ramsay symbolically asserts the Boltons' complete overthrow of the Starks, reinforcing their brutal authority.\n\n3. **Psychological Torture**: Forcing Theon Greyjoy (Reek) to witness the act amplifies Ramsay's control. It serves to further break Theon, reminding him of his powerlessness and solidifying Ramsay's hold over both victims.\n\n4. **Legitimacy and Insecurity**: As a legitimized bastard, Ramsay may feel compelled to prove his worth. Dominating Sansa, a high-born Stark, allows him to assert his status and counteract any lingering insecurity about his origins.\n\n5. **Narrative Context**: The show's adaptation choice to involve Sansa (instead of Jeyne Poole in the books) intensifies the emotional stakes, highlighting the Stark-Bolton feud and Sansa's resilience amid trauma.\n\nThis act underscores Ramsay's role as a quintessential villain, using terror to maintain power while showcasing the horrific consequences of political machinations in Westeros.",
